<paragraph blockId="4.[843,1495,1735,1955]" lastBlockId="6.[117,768,281,402]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="257" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="255" type="description">
Annual herbaceous plant of around half a metre in height. A typical species of the Chaco (
<collectingCountry box="[1146,1225,1768,1792]" name="Bolivia" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1235,1331,1768,1792]" name="Paraguay" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1382,1487,1768,1792]" name="Argentina" pageId="4" pageNumber="255">Argentina</collectingCountry>
) that lives in clearings and the edges of forests and on roadsides; recently published as a new species (
<bibRefCitation author="TOLEDO, J. M. &amp; G. E. BARBOZA" pageId="4" pageNumber="255" pagination="69 - 85" refId="ref12505" refString="TOLEDO, J. M. &amp; G. E. BARBOZA (2005). Novedades en Physalis (Solanaceae). Kurtziana 31: 69 - 85." type="journal article" year="2005">TOLEDO &amp; BARBOZA, 2005: 70-72</bibRefCitation>
). During this investigation no samples corresponding to this species were collected. However, it should be stressed that it grows in the traditional habitats of numerous ethnic groups of the Gran
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="257" type="discussion">
<collectingRegion box="[118,191,281,305]" country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Chaco</collectingRegion>
: ayoreo, chamacoco, lengua, chulupí, wichí and choroti (see exsiccata and map of distribution from 
<bibRefCitation author="TOLEDO, J. M. &amp; G. E. BARBOZA" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" pagination="69 - 85" refId="ref12505" refString="TOLEDO, J. M. &amp; G. E. BARBOZA (2005). Novedades en Physalis (Solanaceae). Kurtziana 31: 69 - 85." type="journal article" year="2005">TOLEDO &amp; BARBOZA, 2005: 72</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[220,282,346,370]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[103,128,1873,1893]" captionTargetBox="[102,1479,279,1774]" captionTargetId="figure-62@5.[242,1339,368,1685]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 2. - Physalis viscosa L. A. A Maká Indian offers information about the plant; C. Ripe fruit with remains of the accrescent calyx; E. A Choroti Indian shows a branch of the plant. Physalis angulata L.; B, D. Branch with fruit. [Photos. A, E: P. Arenas; B-D: V. Friesen]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5748014" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5748014/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); perhaps it is given some of the uses mentioned for the other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[356,443,378,402]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Physalis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="257" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[356,443,378,402]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="257">Physalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the area.
</subSubSection>
